eople and environments. Migrant workers and the remittances they send are vital for many communities across the region. Understanding the scale and nature of private financing is critical for considering the role that different private actors can play and, from the perspective of government, what partnerships, policies and interventions are needed to realize those roles. Across the region, private investment is rising, having doubled in real terms from $305 billion in 2005 to $609 billion in 2015 (Figure 2.8). This is equivalent to an increase from around 14 percent of regional income in 2004 to 22 percent in 2015.75 71 The data show public or publicly guaranteed external debt meaning that the public sector is not always the borrower, but has at least provided a guaranteed of repayment. 72 Cambodia (59 percent of total), Indonesia (52), Lao PDR (58), Myanmar (86) and Viet Nam (60). 73 Lao PDR (36 percent), Thailand (36), Indonesia (35) and the Philippines (33). 74 Comprehensive data are only available for private borrowing from international sources, see Annex, data notes. 75 Calculated as total private investment for the region as a whole divided by the sum of GNI for all countries in the region. 31 Strengthening integrated national financing frameworks to deliver the 2030 Agenda At the national level the picture is mixed. Five countries have seen rises equivalent to a five percentage- point increase in national income or more while in two countries, private investment has increased by more than 10 percentage points. One of these, Indonesia, experienced very rapidly rising investment levels from the late 2000s, with total private investment rising from less than $100 billion a year before 2008 to more than $200 billion a year in 2012. Since then this growth has slowed, though investment levels remain high at over $240 billion in 2015, or around 28 percent of GDP. In other countries, investment levels are growing in absolute volume but have plateaued relative to the economy. In Thailand private investment has been between 16 and 21 percent of GDP every year since 2005. In Viet Nam, it has remained relatively consistent in absolute terms at around $32 billion to $39 billion a year since 2007,76 but has fallen as a proportion of rising national incomes.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dc69f617-01b6-449f-a3d4-06855023a154": {"__data__": {"id_": "dc69f617-01b6-449f-a3d4-06855023a154", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asean-china-undp-financing-sustainable-development-goals-asean", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "ASEAN-China-UNDP Financing the Sustainable Development Goals in ASEAN", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asean-china-undp-financing-sustainable-development-goals-asean", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ac220ae5974b7e552bc654a25a03d041c49c205ec909caa8fae0f95ff76f3d6e"}, "2": {"node_id": "c2fa2fd4-4be7-47e5-8392-8fc8a5a5efc4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asean-china-undp-financing-sustainable-development-goals-asean", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e97f9e19453df3eb5bb8d0e02d7c13524dbe38db066f4b614fa6297d9c3e530b"}}, "hash": "c8ef4eeb4499f35a76aae411a4da577274a76aa683b576291c6fe69c17ed154a", "text": "Lao PDR and Myanmar have had fluctuating levels of private investment; both have seen two periods of high inve